{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4299e64e-de5c-4156-9198-26f00456e3ce","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the CPU profiling preset. From inside the pod:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool (if not already present)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can copy out and analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or **Speedscope** (use `--format speedscope` for the latter).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools in the container, use a **sidecar** or `kubectl cp` the tool in.\n- For deeper OS-level analysis, use **`dotnet-trace`** with `--format speedscope` or pair it with `perf` if the kernel headers are available.\n- To convert later: `dotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope`","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"47b4e759-bd3d-4363-a84a-374ab7b2181b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code task. I'll give a concise answer.","outputTokens":309},"id":"da971c84-4dca-4bbd-ae10-55fc60005af3","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:55:01.315Z","parentId":"74d520ae-79c6-494c-a547-3d4e8ff4e28f"}
